      <section id="section_Typical_Post-Assembly_Considerations_2ifygfaek" class="- topic/section " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="section:7;437:33">
         <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="title:15;440:33">Typical Post-Assembly Considerations</title>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:35;443:25">In vertically-mounted systems under static conditions at room temperature, the mass of a typical heat sink is not usually capable of generating a maximum torque sufficient to detach the lid. However, it is strongly recommend that the customer use a PCB-mounted heat sink solution for vertically mounted boards as the epoxy bond between the lid and the substrate may become weaker in the long term at normal operating conditions.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:36;446:25">Customers should beware of heat sink weight induced shear forces between the package heat spreader and the substrate that can lead to lid detachment as well, even if the torque is below the failure limit. In worst-case situations, the static shear force between the heat spreader lid and the substrate is exerted by the mass of the heat sink and is shown in <xref href="#xd_f8bcb077205a5927--42109557-15cf9f08a40--7ef3/fig_Worst-Case_Static_Shear_on_a_Vertically__3ifygfaek" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="xref:15;449:35" type="fig"><?ditaot gentext?>Figure 7</xref>.</p>
         <note audience="MSCCInternal" class="- topic/note " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="note:4;453:30">
            <xref href="http://bby1dms01.pmc-sierra.internal/DocMgmt/fileinfo.cfm?file_id=434201" scope="external" class="- topic/xref " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="xref:16;458:34"><?ditaot usertext?>http://bby1dms01.pmc-sierra.internal/DocMgmt/fileinfo.cfm?file_id=434201</xref>
         </note>
         <fig id="fig_Worst-Case_Static_Shear_on_a_Vertically__3ifygfaek" class="- topic/fig " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="fig:7;463:28">
            <title class="- topic/title " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="title:16;466:36">Worst-Case Static Shear on a Vertically Mounted Package</title>
            <image href="graphics/trident_heatsink_shear_vert_mnt.svg" width="3.5in" placement="inline" class="- topic/image " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="image:7;472:36"/>
         </fig>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:37;476:25">In this instance, the static shear force between the lid and the substrate may be considered, for simplicity, equivalent in magnitude of the force due to gravity exerted by the heat sink at its center of mass. Although there is torque generated due to the slight offset in the exerted force, the magnitude of this force can be considered minimal due to the very short moment arm between the center of mass of the heat sink and the heat spreader lid-to-substrate interface. Therefore:</p>
         <codeblock xml:space="preserve" class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="codeblock:2;477:196">Static Shear = Fg = m x g</codeblock>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:38;480:25">For a typical large copper heat sink (assuming a typical large heat sink; 5.5cm x 5.5cm; height, h = 3 cm; mass, m = 0.23 kg) we find:</p>
         <codeblock xml:space="preserve" class="+ topic/pre pr-d/codeblock " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="codeblock:3;481:196">Static Shear = (0.23kg) x (9.81m/s<sup class="+ topic/ph hi-d/sup " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="sup:1;481:376">2</sup>) = 2.25 N</codeblock>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:39;484:25">For this analysis it can be seen that the mass of the heat sink alone is not sufficient to cause lid separation, however, it is still strongly recommended that a PCB-mounted heat sink solution be employed in vertically-mounted systems to minimize any potential for induced shear forces between the heat spreader lid and the substrate.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:40;487:25">Please note that in this calculation, the applied force (in the form of weight of the heat sink) is static and applied at room temperature.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\package\trident_package_heatsink_requirements.xml" xtrc="p:41;490:25">In cases of impulsive application of forces, the conclusion drawn above may not be valid. Hence it is strongly recommended that application of impulsive forces or vibrations should be strictly avoided if the board and heat sinks have to be configured in this manner.</p>
